kJqNXp1WjlrNmZrR2tDVzF1NHNNQVdSdWhCOXdybS1RakE?oc=5\"}]','2026-03-26 09:00:40'),(22,'Daily Planet - March 27, 2026','### The Daily Planet\n\n#### Global Affairs: Tensions, Transitions, and Currencies\nThe geopolitical landscape remains volatile as international focus centers on the escalating tensions regarding Iran. Markets reacted with cautious optimism as the Trump administration extended the deadline for negotiations, even as reports detail the complexities of potential nuclear fuel extraction operations. Amid this, the Pentagon’s efforts to blacklist Anthropic have hit a significant legal hurdle; a judge has granted an injunction temporarily blocking the supply-chain-risk designation, marking a notable win for the AI firm in its ongoing struggle with the Defense Department. \n\nElsewhere, the domestic political scene is defined by historical and fiscal shifts: President Trump is set to become the first sitting president to have his signature appear on U.S. currency, while the administration grapples with the fallout of the current government shutdown. On the global stage, Nepal has sworn in a former rapper as prime minister, signaling a generational shift, and in an unusual display of diplomatic signaling, the leader of Belarus has gifted a rifle to North Korea’s Kim Jong Un as the two nations formalize a friendship treaty. Meanwhile, in Australia, the government is scrambling to quell public anxiety over fuel supplies following localized panic buying.\n\n#### Tech & Innovation: Reshuffling and Regulating\nThe tech sector is witnessing a significant shake-up in leadership and hardware philosophy. David Sacks has officially stepped down as the White House AI and Crypto Czar, prompting speculation about his next move. Meanwhile, Apple has confirmed the discontinuation of the Mac Pro, appearing to signal a permanent shift in its workstation strategy. \n\nAI integration continues to draw lines in the sand: while Gemini has introduced a new feature allowing users to seamlessly transfer chat history and personal data from competing chatbots, Wikipedia is moving in the opposite direction, implementing a crackdown on the use of generative AI in article creation to preserve editorial integrity. In the decentralized space, Mastodon is prioritizing accessibility, announcing a major interface revamp designed to lower the barrier to entry for its network.\n\n#### Quick Hits: Notable Mentions\n*   **Culture:** The Oscars are officially departing Hollywood for a new venue, marking an end to an era for the Academy Awards.\n*   **Infrastructure & Policy:** The U.S. Senate has voted to fund portions of the Department of Homeland Security, conspicuously excluding immigration enforcement in a bid to bypass shutdown gridlock.\n*   **Digital Preservation:** A fascinating archival look at 21,864 forgotten Yugoslavian (.yu) domains highlights the fragility of digital history.\n*   **Scientific Observation:** The European AllSky7 fireball network provides a captivating archive for those tracking celestial activity.\n*   **Consumer Tech:** Amazon’s spring sale is currently seeing deep discounts—exceeding 50 percent—on flagship robot vacuums from Eufy and Roborock. \n*   **Tools:** Developers might note the emergence of *jsongrep* as a performant alternative to *jq*, alongside new documentation for scheduling tasks natively on the web.','[{\"title\": \"A Faster Alternative to Jq\", \"url\": \"https://micahkepe.com/blog/jsongrep/\"}, {\"title\": \"Schedule tasks on the web\", \"url\": \"https://code.claude.com/docs/en/web-scheduled-tasks\"}, {\"title\": \"The European AllSky7 fireball network\", \"url\": \"https://www.allsky7.net/#archive\"}, {\"title\": \"21,864 Yugoslavian .yu Domains\", \"url\": \"https://jacobfilipp.com/yu/\"}, {\"title\": \"Apple discontinues the Mac Pro\", \"url\": \"https://9to5mac.com/2026/03/26/apple-discontinues-the-mac-pro/\"}, {\"title\": \"David Sacks is done as AI czar \\u2014 here\\u2019s what he\\u2019s doing instead