\": \"https://news.google.?oc=5\"}]','2026-03-27 09:00:08'),(23,'Daily Planet - March 28, 2026','### Global Affairs: Escalation and Geopolitical Strain\n\nThe international landscape remains dominated by the accelerating war between the U.S.-Israel coalition and Iran, now entering its 29th day. The conflict has widened significantly, marked by a missile attack on a Saudi air base that left at least ten U.S. troops wounded, and a strike by Yemen’s Houthi rebels targeting Israel. Amidst this volatility, domestic U.S. governance faces its own hurdles; the House has narrowly passed a short-term bill to fund the Department of Homeland Security, narrowly averting a complete shutdown, while President Trump has issued an executive order to ensure TSA employees are compensated during the standoff. In other significant global developments, the FBI is managing a major security breach following reports that the Director’s personal communications and sensitive documents were leaked by Iran-linked hackers. Elsewhere, Nepal’s former Prime Minister has been arrested following a fatal crackdown on protesters, and the UN continues to grapple with the definition and condemnation of systemic slavery.\n\n### Tech & Innovation: The Infrastructure of Tomorrow\n\nThe technological sector is increasingly inseparable from the geopolitical maneuvers outlined above, with analysts noting that AI research is beginning to bifurcate along rigid nationalistic lines. Financial markets are closely watching the horizon, as SoftBank’s massive $40 billion loan facility fuels speculation of an imminent OpenAI IPO in 2026. Simultaneously, memory semiconductor giant SK hynix is being positioned as a critical player in stabilizing the global supply chain, with a high-profile U.S. IPO viewed as a potential panacea for the industry’s \"RAMmageddon.\"\n\nIn hardware innovation, AMD is pushing the boundaries of consumer computing with its Ryzen 9 9950X3D2, a chip boasting an extraordinary 208MB of cache. At the frontiers of science, CERN is utilizing specialized, silicon-embedded AI models to perform real-time data filtering for the Large Hadron Collider, proving that the most advanced AI applications are often those requiring the tightest integration with physical infrastructure. \n\n### Quick Hits\n\n*   **Corporate & Market Moves:** Physical Intelligence is reportedly eyeing another $1 billion funding round. Meanwhile, Whoop is aggressively expanding its market reach beyond elite athletes like LeBron James to the broader consumer demographic.\n*   **Consumer Tech:** Sony has temporarily halted sales of specific memory cards due to supply shortages. For those looking for value, the Insta360 Link 2C webcam is seeing significant price cuts, while the Bluetti Sora 500 solar panel continues to impress reviewers with its power-to-size ratio. \n*   **Culture & Lifestyle:** Concerns over \"The Trump Phone\" persist following FCC certification disclosures. Separately, the public conversation surrounding the \"save the bee\" movement continues to gain traction, and Tiger Woods is facing legal repercussions following a DUI charge after a vehicle crash.\n*   **Deals & Utilities:** If you are managing your 2026 expenses, various promotional opportunities are currently circulating for Instacart, Meta Quest, Acer hardware, and Loop earplugs.','[{\"title\": \"Go hard on agents, not on your filesystem\", \"url\": \"https://jai.scs.stanford.edu/\"}, {\"title\": \"AMD\'s Ryzen 9 9950X3D2 Dual Edition crams 208MB of cache into a single chip\", \"url\": \"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2026/03/amds-ryzen-9-9950x3d2-dual-edition-crams-208mb-of-cache-into-a-single-chip/\"}, {\"title\": \"CERN uses tiny AI models burned into silicon for real-time LHC data filtering\", \"url\": \"https://theopenreader.org/Journalism:CERN_Uses_Tiny_AI_Models_Burned_into_Silicon_for_Real-Time_LHC_Data_Filtering\"}, {\"title\": \"The bee that everyone wants to save\", \"url\": \"https://naturalist.bearblog.dev/t