nd Diplomatic Maneuvering\n\nThe geopolitical landscape remains volatile as the 69th day of the Iran war unfolds. In a significant escalation, Israel has conducted strikes on Beirut for the first time since the established Hezbollah ceasefire, while Tehran is reportedly reviewing a U.S. proposal aimed at de-escalation. President Trump has struck a tone of optimism, stating the conflict will be \"over quickly,\" though the situation on the ground remains precarious. Tensions are further punctuated by the movement of a French warship toward the Strait of Hormuz for defensive positioning, as Shell reports a surge in profits directly linked to the conflict’s impact on global energy markets.\n\nElsewhere, the human cost of regional instability continues to mount. In Gaza, the heartbreaking loss of a journalist on the very day of his daughter’s birth highlights the unrelenting tragedy of the conflict. Meanwhile, in Somalia, a convergence of aid cuts, severe drought, and ongoing violence has left a significant portion of the population in dire, desperate conditions. In other international news, a cruise ship is currently diverted to the Canary Islands following a hantavirus outbreak that necessitated the emergency evacuation of three passengers, and a group of women linked to the Islamic State have returned to Australia from Syria.\n\n### Technology and Innovation: The AI Reckoning and Industry Shifts\n\nThe narrative surrounding the AI economy is hitting a period of critical introspection. Industry architects are now openly discussing where the momentum is \"coming off the wheels,\" signaling a maturation—and perhaps a sobering—of the rapid AI expansion. This shifting sentiment is underscored by the dissolution of a major $400 million partnership between Snap and Perplexity, and lingering questions regarding the structural nature of xAI as it positions itself within the cloud infrastructure market.\n\nThe human element remains central to this technological drama: Barry Diller, while expressing personal trust in Sam Altman, has observed that \"trust is irrelevant\" in the shadow of AGI. Simultaneously, internal political fallout continues; in Washington, fallout from David Sacks’ tenure in the Trump administration—particularly regarding AI model reviews—has become a focal point of analysis, while Shivon Zilis’s testimony regarding Elon Musk underscores the complex personal and professional liabilities inherent in the tech titan’s orbit.\n\n### Quick Hits: Notable Mentions\n\n*   **Computing & Hardware:** Valve has released CAD files for the Steam Controller under a Creative Commons license, a boon for the hobbyist community. Additionally, the Library of Congress has officially recognized SQLite as a recommended storage format, cementing its status as an archival standard.\n*   **Gaming:** Nintendo has officially announced a new *Star Fox* title slated for the Switch 2, generating significant excitement among the core fan base. \n*   **Corporate & Policy:** Google has opted to shutter \"Project Mariner.\" On a lighter, albeit more administrative note, discussions regarding the performance-theatre of \"appearing productive\" in the modern workplace continue to strike a chord with the remote-work generation.\n*   **Sports:** The San Antonio Spurs, led by the irrepressible Victor Wembanyama, have leveled their series against the Timberwolves in the NBA Playoffs.\n*   **Consumer Deals:** A variety of promotional offers are currently active for the month of May, ranging from discounts at Walmart (65%) and Groupon (60%) to bundle savings on AT&T services and specialized savings on hardware like the Tile Pro tracker.','[{\"title\": \"Valve releases Steam Controller CAD files under Creative Commons license\", \"url\": \"https://www.digitalfoundry.net/news/2026/05/valve-releases-steam-controller-cad-files-under-creative-commons-license\"}, {\"title\": \"Appearing productive in the workplace\", \"url\": \"https://nooneshappy.com/article/appearing-productive-in-the-workplace/\"}, {\"title\": \"Permacomputing Principles\", \"url\": \"https://permacomputing.net/principles/\"}, {\"title\": \"SQLite Is a Library of Congress Recommended Storage Format\", \"url\": \"https://sqlite.org/locrsf.html\"}, {\"title\": \"Diskless Linux boot using ZFS, iSCSI and PXE\", \"url\": \"https://aniket.foo/posts/20260505-netboot/\"}, {\"title\": \"Five architects of the AI economy explain where the wheels are coming off\", \"url\": \"https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/06/five-architects-of-the-ai-economy-explain-where-the-wheels-are-coming-off/\"}, {\"title\": \"A 20-minute pitch wins Indian startup Pronto backing from Lachy Groom\", \"url\": \"https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/06/a-20-minute-pitch-wins-indian-startup-pronto-backing-from-lachy-groom/\"}, {\"title\": \"Barry Diller trusts Sam Altman. But \\u2018trust is irrelevant\\u2019 as AGI nears, he says.\", \"url\": \"https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/06/barry-diller-trusts-sam-altman-but-trust-is-irrelevant-as-agi-nears-he-says/\"}, {\"title\": \"Snap says its $400M deal with Perplexity \\u2018amicably ended\\u2019\", \"url\": \"https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/06/snap-says-its-400m-deal-with-perplexity-amicably-ended/\"}, {\"title\": \"Is xAI a neocloud now?\", \"url\": \"https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/06/is-xai-a-neocloud-now/\"}, {\"title\": \"Musk\\u2019s biggest loyalist became his biggest liability\", \"url\": \"https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/925665/musk-altman-trial-shivon-zilis-testimony\"}, {\"title\": \"Nintendo announces a new Star Fox for the Switch 2\", \"url\": \"https://www.theverge.com/entertainment/925601/star-fox-nintendo-switch-2\"}, {\"title\": \"Google shuts down Project Mariner\", \"url\": \"https://www.theverge.com/tech/925559/google-project-mariner-shut-down\"}, {\"title\": \"How David Sacks crashed and burned in the White House\", \"url\": \"https://www.theverge.com/column/925487/david-sacks-trump-administration-ai-model-review\"}, {\"tit